# M5Basic_Stepper

A motor control project using the **M5Stack Basic** and a **TB6600 stepper driver**, with on-screen status display and button-based control.

---

## ğŸš€ Features

- ğŸŸ¢ **Button A**: Start/Stop the stepper motor
- ğŸ”„ **Button B**: Toggle direction (CW/CCW)
- â›” **Button C**: Toggle driver enable/disable
- ğŸ“º **Display**: Real-time status of motor, direction, and driver state
- ğŸ§  Built with `M5Unified` and `PlatformIO`

---

## ğŸ§° Hardware Used

| Component         | Description                          |
|------------------|--------------------------------------|
| M5Stack Basic     | ESP32-based development core         |
| TB6600 Driver     | Stepper motor driver (5V logic)      |
| NEMA 23 Stepper   | 57J1856-430-8 or similar              |
| Power Supply      | 12â€“24V for motor + 5V logic (if needed) |

---

## ğŸ§© Wiring Overview

| M5Stack GPIO | TB6600 Pin | Function        |
|--------------|------------|-----------------|
| GPIO 5       | ENA-       | Enable (active LOW) |
| GPIO 17      | DIR-       | Direction        |
| GPIO 16      | PUL-       | Step pulse       |
| GND          | ENA-/DIR-/PUL- | Common ground   |
| 5V (optional)| ENA+       | Logic HIGH (via level shifter if needed) |

> âš ï¸ Note: The ESP32 outputs 3.3V logic. To fully disable the TB6600 via ENA+, a 5V HIGH signal is required. A level shifter or transistor circuit may be needed.

